<DOC><DOCNO> AP890130-0244 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 1439EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f AM-Poll-Method Bjt   01-30 0555</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Poll-Method, Bjt,0573</SECOND><HEAD>Method Used in Poll on Air Safety</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Poll-Air Terror Bjt. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   This Media General-Associated Press poll is basedon telephone interviews Jan. 4-12 with 1,162 adults in thecontinental United States.   The phone numbers were selected randomly by computer andinterviews were conducted with the adult who had the most recentbirthday.   The results were weighted to adjust for variations in the sample.The poll has a 3-point margin of error, meaning that if every adultAmerican were asked the same questions, the results theoreticallywould be within 3 points of the poll's results, 19 times out of 20.The error margin is larger for subgroups _ 4 points for men, forexample.   There are other sources of potential error in polls, includingthe wording and order of questions. These are the questions andresponses in this poll; because of rounding, sums may not total 100:   1. Generally, do you think airline security on internationalflights is adequate, or not? Yes: 28 percent. No: 56 percent. Don'tknow or no answer: 16 percent.   2. The federal government has directed U.S. airlines to X-ray allchecked baggage on flights from Europe and the Mideast. Shouldforeign airlines be required to do the same thing? Yes: 96. No: 2.DK-NA: 2.   3. Would you support or oppose requiring airlines to hand-searchall checked baggage on international flights, even if that meanspassengers have to show up three hours before takeoff? Support: 73.Oppose: 22. DK-NA: 5.   4. Would you support or oppose a ban on carry-on luggage oninternational flights? Support: 49. Oppose: 45. DK-NA: 7.   5. Should the U.S. government publicly announce all terroristthreats it receives against airlines, even if it gets such threatson a daily basis and cannot tell if they're legitimate? Yes: 45. No:45. DK-NA: 9.   6. How about the airlines _ should they be required to announceall terrorist threats they receive? Yes: 57. No: 38. DK-NA: 6.   7. If the United States has proof that another country supporteda terrorist group that attacked U.S. citizens, should the U.S. takemilitary action against that country? Yes: 55. No: 30. DK-NA: 15.   a. (If yes) Would you feel that way even if the U.S. militaryaction might kill innocent people in the other country? Yes: 60. No:31. DK-NA: 10.   8. If the United States believes that another country supported aterrorist group that attacked U.S. citizens, but has no directproof, should the U.S. take military action against that country?Yes: 9. No: 84. DK-NA: 7.   9. If the United States strikes militarily against countries thatit believes support terrorism, do you think that will increaseterrorist attacks, decrease them, or make no difference? Increase:31. Decrease: 34. No Difference: 27. DK-NA: 8.   10. Do you think the U.S. government is doing all it can toprotect American citizens against terrorism, or should it be doingmore? All it can: 36. More: 57. DK-NA: 7.   11. Do you think the U.S. government can do anything tosignificantly reduce terrorist attacks that affect Americancitizens, or not? Can: 61. Cannot: 26. DK-NA: 13.   12. Which do you think poses a greater danger to air travelers _terrorism or inadequate airplane maintenance? Terrorism: 24.Maintenance: 64. DK-NA: 12.</TEXT></DOC>